Abstract: This report seeks to describe and analyze the development of agriculture in Morocco since 1956.  The author spent December 1959 to April 1965 as chief of the agriculture division, U.S. AID Mission to Morocco, and previously had served as the agriculture member of the U.S. survey team in 1956 to determine aid requirements.  This report emphasizes development planning and the establishment and reform of agricultural institutions such as extension, education, cooperatives, credit, and land tenure, to implement the objectives of development. Abstract: This is a training manual for police.  The methods included in this text are emergency procedures not utilized in a normal, peace-time situation.  They are stringent, war-time measures designed to assist in defeating the enemy and helping the people of Vietnam.  The material contained in this text should be used both as a basis for establishing a control system and for giving training to the officers and men charged with the responsibility of placing it into effect.  Chapters include the following topics: the role of the civil police in counterinsurgency (nature of the problem, the enemy and how he operates, the strategic hamlet, and rural police -- function and administration); resources control -- regulation of the movement of people and goods (gaining support for the program, passes and manifests, identity cards and family registration, check points and searches, fire prevention and protection for the rural policeman, and evacuation/alarms/curfews); and the Malayan experience (the report, what the authors say, the statutes, the planning process, and the reorganization of the national police).  (Combined Arms Research Library abstract)

Abstract: Evaluates a final report submitted by the contractor Dalton-Dalton Associates covering the period 4/4/63 to 10/10/63 in Nigeria. Dalton-Dalton is an architectural firm contracted to design the Port Harcourt Comprehensive Secondary School.  Their performance was excellent.  They designed a functional plant of pleasing appearance that is still low in cost. The design submitted was criticized by the architectural staff of the Government of Eastern Nigeria (GOEN) as being unsatisfactory due to their unfamiliarity with the unusual method selected by the architect to achieve maximum air movement and low building costs while still maintaining good student traffic movement.  They were concerned about the effectiveness of the design in securing air circulation and the possibility of a high noise level. The USAID engineering staff considered the architects solution to be satisfactory and sent clippings from several major architectural journals for their review which showed successful application of this design in regions of the US having a similar climate problem to the GOEN.  The design was then accepted by the GOEN. A major problem to the architect and to USAID on this project was caused by inability of the University contractor, UCLA, to make up their mind on functional requirements of the Trades and Industry Building. After jointly preparing preliminary designs in writing, they had second thoughts and wanted to change their minds.  Evaluator notes that this practice is still continuing to a certain extent and should be stopped.

Abstract: This report, one of 23 country studies conducted as part of a worldwide evaluation survey, reviews A.I.D.'s participant training program in Bolivia.  The study was based on interviews of 701 of 1,422 returnees, 170 supervisors, and 19 U.S. technicians.  Included are recommendations in the areas of training design, third- and in-country training, pre-departure preparation, English language, orientation, follow-up, and professional development. Abstract: Project to promote private investment in Colombia.  The project will make U.S. dollars available to the Bank of the Republic for lending to the private sector through the Private Investment Fund, which helps intermediary credit institutions (e.g., commercial banks, financieras) make loans to businesses for purposes which include (1) diversification and export promotion, (2) improved production, and (3) import substitution.

Document Title: Policy paper : extended risk guaranties of loans for private projects (other than housing projects)
Category: Document Type~Document Type Collection~Program Related Reports (all)~USAID Policy Document

Abstract: After achieving independence in 1947, India adopted as its first goal improvement of the living, standard of its now more than 450 million citizens.  Working through democratic institutions it has organized coordinated economic and social development projects under its comprehensive Five-Year Programs, inaugurated in 1951.  Its objectives are production of more food, building of a broad industrial base, creation of new employment opportunities, education of the Indian people, improvement in health conditions, and development of sound social institutions to promote the general welfare.  At India's request, the United States is assisting to achieve these goals. U.S. aid plays a supporting role in many areas: railways, mining, seed improvement, malaria eradication, training future university professors, instruction in industrial crafts.  The forms of aid have changed with the changing needs of India, as well as changes in methods of administration of U.S. foreign aid programs.  This report covers the various phases of U.S. economic aid to India.  (author abstract)

Abstract: This report, one of 23 country studies conducted as part of a worldwide survey, reviews A.I.D.'s participant training program in Chile from 1943 to 1960.  The report was based on oral interviews with 429 of 1,234 returned participants and 199 supervisors and contains recommendations in the areas of training design, pre-departure, and English language training. Abstract: AID PROVIDES LOAN TO CONSTRUCT TWO RELATED HIGHWAYS, ONE APPROXIMATELY 206 KILOMETERS FROM COCHABAMBA TO THE ISOBORO RIVER NEAR PUERTO PATINO (PAVED FROM COCHABAMBA TO VILLA TUNARI) AND THE SECOND ALL GRAVEL OF APPROXIMATELY 93 KILOMETERS FROM VILLA TUNARI TO PORT ON ICHILO RIVER. ICHILO IS NAVIGABLE YEAR ROUND AND IS PART OF MAMORE SYSTEM, MAIN TRANSPORTATION ARTERY FOR TROPICAL BOLIVIA. HIGHWAYS COULD BE INCORPORATED IN PROPOSED "MARGINAL HIGHWAY OF THE JUNGLE" AND SERVE AS TRUNK ROUTE FROM COCHABAMBA TO SANTA CRUZ.

Abstract: EXPANSION OF AGRICULTURAL PRODUCTION IS A PRIORITY OBJECTIVE OF GOP. LIVESTOCK AND SMALL FARM NEEDS ARE BEING CARED FOR BY OTHER EXTERNAL ASSISTANCE. USAID CREDIT ASSISTANCE WILL BE DIRECTED TO MIDDLE AND LARGE SIZE COMMERCIAL FARMS. BESIDES MAKING FUNDS AVAILABLE, USAID IS DESIROUS OF CHANGING CERTAIN FISCAL AND ADMINISTRATIVE PRACTICES WHICH IT PERCEIVES AS DETRIMENTAL. THE TOTAL SUM OF THE LOAN IS BEING TRANCHED, WITH EACH INCREMENT BEING RELEASED SUBJECT OT SATISFACTORY PERFORMANCE IN PRESCRIBED AREAS.

Abstract: BRAZIL IS PROVIDED WITH US PARTICIPANT TRAINING AND TECHNICAL ADVISORY ASSISTANCE TO DEVELOP INSTITUTIONAL CAPABILITY TOPROVIDE HIGH QUALITY ENGINEERING TRAINING AT POST GRADUATE LEVEL. ASSISTANCE WILL GO TO TWO UNIVERSITIES - FEDERAL UNIVERSITY AT RIO DE JANERIO/GRADUATE ENGINEERING SCHOOL FURJ/COPPE) AND PONTIFICA UNIVERSITY OF RIO DE JANEIRO (PUC) TO DEVELOP FULL-TIME, WELL QUALIFIED TRAINING STAFFS AND IMPROVE RESEARCH AND ADMINISTRATIVE PRACTICES. (PROJECT EMPHASIS HAS SHIFTED FROM INCREASING NUMBERS OF STUDENTS TO UPGRADING FACULTIES). USAID WILL CONTRACT FULL-TIME PROFESSORS TO SERVE ON GRADUATE ENGINEERING TEACHERS STAFFS AND PROVIDE SCHOLARSHIPS FOR ADVANCED TRAINING FOR PUC AND FUJR PROFESSORS. SHORT-TERM CONSULTANTS WILL ALSO BE PROVIDED. PRIORITY FIELDS INCLUDE INDUSTRIAL, MECHANICAL, METALLURGICAL, ELECTRICAL AND TRANSPORTATION ENGINEERING. ASSISTANCE WILL FOCUS ON CREATION OF ELECTRICAL ENGINEERING LABORATORY AT PUC AND REFORMATION OF ITS MECHANICAL AND INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING PROGRAMS. AT FURJ, THERMODYNAMICS AND INDUSTRIAL ENGINEERING LABORATORIES WILL BE REFORMED. COOPERATION BETWEEN PUC AND FURJ AND OTHER BRAZILIAN UNIVERSITIES WITH ADVANCED PROGRAMS IN ENGINEERING WILL BE ENCOURAGED. US CONTRACT PERSONNEL WILL GIVE SHORT COURSES AND SEMINARS AT OTHER ENGINEERING INSTITUTIONS AND THOSE CONDUCTED AT PUC AND FURJ WILL BE OPEN TO STAFF MEMBERS FROM OTHER INSTITUTIONS. TWO UNIVERSITIES HAVE RECEIVED ASSISTANCE FOR THEIR ENGINEERING PROGRAMS FROM VARIETY OF SOURCES. BRAZILIAN GOVERNMENT HAS CONSTRUCTED FACILITIES AND PROVIDED BUDGETARY MAINTENANCE. SCHOLARSHIPS AND EQUIPMENT HAVE BEEN FURNISHED BY OTHER GOVERNMENT AGENCIES AND RESEARCH GRANTS BY PRIVATE INDUSTRIES. TEACHING GRANTS HAVE ALSO BEEN OFFERED BY ORGANIZATION OF AMERICAN STATES, ROCKEFELLER FOUNDATION AND FULBRIGHT COMMISSION. FURJ HAS RECIEVED ASSISTANCE FROM SEVERAL OTHER FOREIGN GOVERNMENTS. USAID TRAINING GRANTS HAVE BEEN SCALED DOWN BECAUSE OF AVAILABILITY OF GRANTS FROM BRAZILIAN GOVERNMENT AGENCIES.

Abstract: Project to help the Government of Costa Rica (GOCR) to accelerate tax mapping/appraisal and topographic mapping projects.  Property identification maps and valuation appraisals will be completed for an area which contains 90% of Costa Rica's taxable value. Topographic mapping, when completed, will be used for public works/land use planning.  The GOCR's Direct Tax Appraisal Division and its Instituto Geografico will implement the project.

Abstract: LOAN IS EXTENDED TO HONDURAS TO FINANCE AGRICULTURAL RELENDING PROGRAM AND CONSTRUCTION OF GRAIN STORAGE FACILITIES. PROJECT CONSISTS OF CONSTRUCTION OF TWO CENTRAL AND SEVERAL REGIONAL STORAGE FACILITIES AND TRAINING OF TECHNICAL AND MANGERIAL PERSONNEL ESSENTIAL TO THEIR OPERATION. AGRICULTURAL RELENDING PROGRAM WILL PROVIDE INCREASED AMOUNT OF CREDIT TO SMALL FARMERS BOTH DIRECTLY AND THROUGH COOPERATIVES FOR PURCHASE OF FERTILIZER, ESTICIDE AND IMPROVED SEED. TRAINING IS ALSO PROVIDED TO IMPROVE AGRICULTURAL TECHNIQUE OF SMALL FARMERS.

Abstract: LOAN TO GOVERNMENT OF PANAMA (GOP) SUPPORTS DISSEMINATION OF MODERN AGRICULTURAL TECHNOLOGY,IMPROVED FARMING PRACTICES,AND CREDIT AMONG THE SUBSISTENCE FARMERS. DURING 3-YEAR DISBURSEMENT PERIOD,LOAN SUPPORTS EFFORTS IN 5 MAJOR AREAS: 1)IN AREA OF TECHNOLOGICAL DEVELOPMENTS SUPPORT,US TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE IN AGRICULTURAL RESEARCH & EXTENSION ACTIVITIES PROVIDED,AS ARE TA & EQUIPMENT FOR DEVELOPMENT OF PILOT IRRIGATION PROJECTS; ALSO ASSISTED ARE EXPANSION OF IMPROVED SEEDS & EQUIPMENT RENTAL PROGRAMS AND CONSTRUCTION OF AN ANIMAL DISEASE CONTROL LABORATORY.2)TECHNICAL EDUCATION COMPONENT PROVIDES FOR CONSTRUCTION,PERSONNEL, & EQUIPMENT TO EXPAND THE NATIONAL SCHOOL OF AGRICULTURE AND TO DOUBLE THE PRESENT NUMBER OF ADULT TRAINING FACILITIES FOR SHORT-TERM EXTENSION COURSES. ALSO SUPPORTED ARE US & 3RD-COUNTRY SCHOLARSHIPS FOR SPECIALIZED AND/OR GRADUATE TRAINING.3)US TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE PROVIDED IN AREA OF MARKETING IMPROVEMENT TO DEVELOP STANDARDIZED SYSTEMS OF CROP GRADING,IMPLEMENT PROGRAMS OF MARKET & PRICE NEWS,PROVIDE CROP FORECASTS, & DEVELOP PRODUCTION COST STUDIES. EQUIPMENT & PERSONNEL ALSO PROVIDED FOR MINISTRY OF AGRICULTURE SPONSORED VEGETABLE MARKETING PROGRAM.4)AVAILABILITY OF SMALL FARMER CREDIT IS IMPROVED BY $1 MILLION INCREASE TO SUPERVISED CREDIT FUND.5)POLICY AND PROGRAM DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITIES CALL FOR TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO GOP IN THE DEVELOPMENT OF A COMPREHENSIVE SECTOR POLICY. LOAN IS ADMINISTERED BY THE MINISTRY OF AGRICULTURE,COMMERCE, AND INDUSTRIES. THE INSTITUTO DE FOMENTO ECONOMICO PROVIDES BANKING SERVICES NECESSARY FOR THE ADMINISTRATION OF THE SUPERVISED AGRICULTURAL CREDIT FUND. DISSEMINATION OF CREDIT AND IMPROVED AGRICULTURAL PRACTICES WILL IMMEDIATELY BENEFIT THE RURAL POOR, AND SHOULD HAVE LONG-TERM EFFECTS ON ALL ASPECTS OF PANAMANIAN SOCIETY.

Abstract: EVALUATES THE PERFORMANCE OF A PROJECT CONTRACTOR, SMITH, HINCHMAN & GRYLLS ASSOCIATES, INC(SHG), FOR THE PERIOD 4/1/64-10/1/64. PURPOSE OF PROJECT WAS TO DEVELOP A VIABLE HEALTH SCIENCES (MEDICAL/DENTAL) CENTER IN VIETNAM. THE METHODOLOGY USED FOR THIS EVALUATION WAS UNSPECIFIED. SHG EXECUTED ALL ITS RESPONSIBILITIES CAPABLY. ITS ENTIRE STAFF WAS COMPETENT AND EFFICIENT AND HAD EXCELLENT LEADERSHIP. THEIR RELATIONSHIPS WITH THE GVN,LOCAL WORKERS AND THEIR EMPLOYERS(PROJECT CONSTRUCTORS),AND THE USOM WAS VERY GOOD. EXCELLENT COOPERATION IN BUILDING MAINTENANCE WAS GIVEN TO USOM TRAINEES BY SHG STAFF. CONSTRUCTION PROGRESS REMAINED ON SCHEDULE DESPITE SEVERAL LOCAL CIVIL DISTURBANCES AND THE DETENTION OF ONE OF THE PRINCIPAL CONTRACTORS BY LOCAL AUTHORITIES. THE AVOIDANCE OF CONSTRUCTION SLOWDOWNS WAS DUE IN PART TO THE CLOSE COORDINATION OF SHG AND THE CONSTRUCTORS. CONSTRUCTION WORK COMPLTRUCTION WORK COMPLETED TO DATE WAS OF GOOD QUALITY. THE GVN HAS LIVED UP TO ITS FUNDING COMMITMENTS AND HAS PROVIDED SUPPORT ON SCHEDULE.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1 APR 1964-1 OCT 1964

Abstract: Evaluates the performance of a proj contractor, Robt R Nathan Associates, Inc (RRN), from 3/64 to 9/64.  Proj was intended to strengthen the capability of several Govt of Afghanistan ministries (particularly the Min of Planning-MOP) for designing & executing developmental projects. The performance of RRN appeared highly satisfactory.  Contractor's local team established good working relations with GOA personnel; this team displayed high professional competence and, with good backstopping from its US headquarters, was able to meet its contractual commitments fully and promptly.  GOA's satisfaction with RRN is displayed by its reliance upon RRN assistance for an appraisal of current inflationary pressures, an analysis of current budgetary deficits, and an examination of the feasibility of select projects. Services (or achievements) provided by RRN during this eval period include:  1) directly assisting the MOP with the preparation of projects, eg, the enlarged rural credit program; 2) advising the Min of Agr on its revised research program and on special programs to increase wheat production, develop a dairy processing plant in Kabul, and implement an agr sample census; 3) assisting with efforts to improve the work of assembling, processing & publishing economic statistics; 4) preparing a proposal for the review of the GOA's second Five-Year Plan and presenting this proposal to the MOP; 5) assisting select GOA personnel with the development of curricula in econ planning and providing these personnel with on-the-job training; 6) conducting relevant participant training programs.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 22 Mar 1964-21 Sep 1964

Abstract: Evaluates project performance from 9/22/63 to 3/22/64 in Afghanistan. Contractor provided technical assistance to the Royal Government of Afghanistan (RGA) to develop administrative procedures and assist Afghanistan run its economic program. Methodology not defined. Evaluator feels Robert R Nathan Associates, Inc (RRNA), the contractor, has a clear understanding of the scope and nature of the project. RRNA has performed satisfactorily from both RGA's and USAID/A's standpoint, developing goals which assure completion of contract objectives within the contract period.  RGA has demonstrated its confidence in RRNA by asking them to brief officials from other organizations such as IMF, UNESCO, US, etc on Afghanistan's economic situation. RRNA has adequate leadership in its home office and harmonious and effective working relations not only with RGA but also with other contract groups such as PAS and USAID/A. Under RRNA leadership, RGA's economic planning and general economic coordination has been organized in the Ministry of Planning. Program has resulted in on-the-job training which has adequately prepared Afghans to administer economic programs after contract termination. Equipment has been wisely selected and kept in repair.  All requests and required reports in regards to RGA and USAID/A situations have been submitted on time to AID/W by RRNA. Evaluator feels it is likely that the US will want to extend the contract in order to retain its influence in the Ministry of Planning.

Abstract: This report is one of twenty-three country studies conducted as part of the worldwide survey of returned participants in accordance with AID/W instructions and guidelines contained in ICATO Circular A-175, November 1959.  The major purpose of this global effort was to obtain an overview of how the participant training program was progressing to ascertain ways in which future training might be more effective at the country, AID/W, and training institution levels.  This evaluation report examines the level, quality, and relevance of the training program; determines whether participants were returning to positions for which they were trained, and whether they were utilizing and transmitting their training; and identifies the important factors hindering the utilization and communication of training.  This study also includes information about participants' experiences during training and their activities after returning to Turkey. Interviews were conducted with 1,202 returned Turkish participants.  Several good recommendations are concluded in the areas of training design, pre-departure preparation, and English language training.  (Author abstract)

Abstract: Evaluates project performance from 1/6/62 to 9/14/65 in Pakistan. The University of Hawaii assists the Government of Pakistan develop its vocational and skilled educational program through staff instruction, building construction, curriculum development, and procurement of necessary equipment.  Evaluation methodology not defined. Evaluator feels contractor has performed well, promptly submitted all necessary reports, and has a clear understanding of contract objectives. Preparation and plans have been made to complete the short term goals on schedule.  Trainees in the two centers at Decca and Karachi have begun their second year of training under technically competent staff who are making notable contributions in auto mechanics, refrigeration, and air-conditioning. Project advisor and Pakistan staff have close working relationships with the Hawaii group, while contractor's staff has developed a good working relationship both with the Government of Pakistan and USAID personnel.  Most of the equipment for the two training centers has been procured due to persistent efforts of Hawaii and Pakistan staff. Delays which have occurred are in no way the fault of the contractor. The completion of a long awaited pattern-foundry building at both centers is not progressing due to delays in the Government of West Pakistan to sanction the funds.  Equipment procurement problems likewise have resulted from delays in dock clearance. Government of Pakistan is satisfied with the Hawaii team's performance and is negotiating an extension to the contract.

Abstract: GUATEMALA HAS PERHAPS THE MOST ADVANCED PROGRAM OF RUBBER BREEDING AND TESTING IN THE AMERICAS. TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE OF HIGH QUALITY IS AVAILABLE TO PLANTERS. PRODUCTION PROGRAM WAS DEVELOPED WITH GUIDANCE OF USDA AND AID TECHNICIANS WHO CONTINUE TO ADVISE ON RESEARCH, EXTENSION AND DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS. AID TECHNICIANS INSPECT EACH PLANTING SITE FOR ECOLOGICAL SUITABILITY FOR RUBBER PRODUCTION BEFORE LOAN IS GRANTED. AFTER APPROVAL OF LOAN, TECHNICIANS ADVISE ON PLANTING STOCK, FIELD LAYOUT, AND CULTURAL PRACTICES. NORMALLY EACH FARM IS VISITED THREE TIMES FIRST YEAR AND ONCE A YEAR THEREAFTER. SHORT COURSES ARE PROVIDED ON PLANTATION AND NURSERY MANAGEMENT. RUBBER TAPPING AND PROCESSING.

Abstract: Project to strengthen demographic research in Latin America.  The Centro Latinamericano de Demografia (CELADE) will:  (1) establish national institutes of demography in Latin American countries; (2) teach demography to as many students as possible, adding a new third year course; (3) assist countries with population planning through arrangements with trainees; and (4) upon request, provide technical and financial assistance for field studies and research projects.

Abstract: This report is one of twenty-three country studies conducted as part of the worldwide survey of returned participants in accordance with AID/W instructions and guidelines contained in ICATO Circular A-175, November 1959.  The major purpose of this global effort was to obtain an overview of how the participant training program was progressing to ascertain ways in which future training might be effective at the country, AID/W, and training institution levels.  The study included interviews with 402 returned participants along with 163 supervisors and U.S. technicians.  This is a good report with solid recommendations in nearly all the major areas of participant training.  (Participant training abstract)

Abstract: CAPITAL ASSISTANCE PROVIDED TO THE ECUADOR COOPERATIVE BANK TO BE UTILIZED TO FINANCE SUB-LOANS TO BANKS COOPERATIVE MEMBERS AS A STRATEGY FOR INCREASING AGRICULTURAL AND INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION. PROJECT DISGINED TO BENEFIT LOWER-MIDDLE CLASS ECUADORIANS WHO HAVE LITTLE ACCESS TO CREDIT AT REASONABLE TERMS. STIMULATES CREDIT UNION MOVEMENT AND ESTABLISHES REVENUE PRODUCING, SELF FINANCING CREDIT INSTITUTIONS THAT WILL INFLUENCE ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT OF ECUADOR. PROJECT PAPER INCLUDES HISTORY AND BACKGROUND OF COOPERATIVE MOVEMENT IN ECUADOR, DESCRIPTION OF SUB-LOAN PROJECTS AND A HISTORY OF THE ECUADOR COOPERATIVE BANK.

Abstract: NATL SEED LAW PASSED IN 1965 REGARDING SEED STANDARDS; A SYSTEM OF OFFICIAL REGULATORY LABORATORIES IS UNDERWAY WITH 10 OF THE 14 LABS IN OPERATION. MISSISSIPPI STATE, THE IMPLEMENTING AGENT WILL HELP DEVELOP REGULATIONS. EXTENSION SEED INFO SPECIALISTS WILL BE TRAINED BY CONTRACT TEAM NEW SEED COMPANIES, EXPANSION OF EXISTING COMPANIES DECREASE GOVT SALES; TECHNICIANS FROM PRIVATE COMPANIES RECEIVE INFO ON SEED MKTG AND MACHINERY. SEED LAW SHOULD ENCOURAGE MORE PRIVATE INDUSTRY. COORDINATED RESEARCH ACTIVITIES PLANNED FOR VARIETAL TESTING. GRADUATE AND TRAINING PROGRAMS IN SEED TECHNOLOGY DEVELOPED AT THE UNIV OF SAO PAULO.OFFICIAL SEED MULTIPLICATION ORGANIZATIONS ESTABLISHED IN SOUTHERN STATES TO CERTIFY SEEDS.

Abstract: LOAN PROVIDED TO THE GOVT OF TURKEY'S TURKIYE CUMHURIYETI DEVLET DEMIRYOLLARI (TCDD), THE GENERAL DIRECTORATE OF TURKISH STATE RAILWAYS, FOR THE INSTALLATION OF A CENTRAL TRAFFIC CONTROL (CTC) SYSTEM ON THE TCDD'S HAYDARPASA (ISTANBUL) -ANKARA RAIL LINE AND A COMMUNICATION SYSTEM ON THE ANKARA-ZONGULDAK LINE. THIS PROJ COMPLETES THE CTC INSTALLATION WORK BEGUN UNDER AN EARLIER PROJ AND LATER DISCONTINUED DUE TO A CONTRACT DISPUTE BETWEEN THE TCDD AND THE PROJ CONTRACTOR, THE WESTINGHOUSE AIR BRAKE INTERNATIONAL CORPORATION (WABIC) . SPECIFICALLY, THIS PROJ WILL PROVIDE FOR THE INSTALLATION OF: 1) A WAYSIDE SYSTEM FOR ELECTRIFIED TRACTION IN THE HAYDARPASA-ARIFIYE-ADAPAZARI TERRITORY AND FOR NON-ELECTRIFIED TRACTION IN THE ARIFIYE-ANKARA TERRITORY; 2) CONTROL MACHINES; 3) A CODE CONTROL AND INDICATION SYSTEM; 4) A DISPATCHER'S PHONE, STATION-TO-STATION BLOCK PHONE, MAINTENANCE PHONE INCLUDING PORTABLE TELEPHONE, AND HIGH FREQUENCY CARRIER SYSTEM -- ALL FOR THE HAYDARPASA-ARIFIYE-ADAPAZARI-ANKARA TERRITORY; 5) DISPATCHER'S PHONE AND STA-TO-STA BLOCK PHONE FOR THE ANKARA-IRMAK TERRITORY; AND 6) A HIGH-FREQUENCY CARRIER SYSTEM IN THE ANKARA-IRMAK-CATALAGZI (ZONGULDAK) TERRITORY. WABIC WILL CONTINUE AS THE MAIN CONTRACTOR FOR THIS PROJECT AND WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR PROCURING THE NECESSARY CTC AND COMMUNICATIONS EQUIPMENT. WABIC WILL ALSO HELP TCDD PERSONNEL TO INSTALL THE CTC AND MOST OF THE COMMUNICATION EQUIPMENT; THE GERMAN FIRM OF TELEFUNKEN WILL INSTALL THE HIGH-FREQUENCY CARRIER SYSTEM. UNION SWITCH AND SIGNAL, A DIVISON OF WABIC'S PARENT COMPANY, THE WESTINGHOUSE AIR BRAKE CO, WILL DESIGN THE CTC SYSTEM AND SERVE AS THE MANUFACTURER AND SUPPLIER FOR MOST OF THE EQUIPMENT (THE EXCEPTIONS BEING AXLE COUNTER MACHINES FROM SWITZERLAND AND ALUMINUM-SHEATHED CABLE FROM OTHER EUROPEAN SOURCES). WABIC ON-SITE ADVISORS WILL TRAIN TCCD PERSONNEL TO MAINTAIN THE EQUIPMENT. ONE WABIC REPRESENTATIVE WILL REMAIN IN TURKEY FOR 1-1/2 YEARS AFTER COMPLETION OF THE CTC SYSTEM TO ENSURE ITS SATISFACTORY OPERATION.

Abstract: Loan is provided to the Government of Taiwan to construct a run-of-river hydroelectric project in the Chingsan reach of the Tachia River in Taiwan. The Taiwan Power Company (Taipower) will implement the project. A total of 295 meters of head remaining in the Chingshan reach of the Tachia River will be developed between the proposed Upper Tachien Reservoir Project and the existing Kukuan Reservoir project.  The main dam and intake will be constructed on the Tachia Rivers, and a diversion structure will be constructed on Chihloh Creek.  The planned 45 meter-high concrete gravity dam will impound the inflows of the Tachia River to normal maximum headwater elevation 1245.  The diversion structure will consist of a 5,500 meter-long, 6.6 meter diameter headtunnel, which will divert the flows of the Tachia River and Chihloh Creek and provide adequate pondage to regulate natural inflows for daily peaking operations during the system's critical period.  An underground power station will be constructed containing two 90 megawatt (MW) units. The station will consist of a 97 meter-long by 17.5 meter-wide excavated chamber, including a machine hall, erection bay, and control room. Two additional 90 MW units will be installed in the station when the Upper Tachien Reservoir project is completed.  In addition, a short length transmission line will be installed to tie the Lower Tachien project into the island-wide network at Kukuan.  This project will have a total reservoir volume of 1,170,000 cubic meters (cm), with 690,000 cm in active storage before sedimentation and 590,000 cm in active storage after sedimentation. Taipower will employ local contractors for the civil engineering works.

Abstract: Presents a brief history of the development of the University of Nigeria from its inception in 1/60 to 6/64.  The report also evaluates performance of Michigan State University (MSU) which was contracted to assist in development of the total university.  This included developing the administrative organization, curricula, and faculty. Planning for the project has been excellent.  The project has developed at a very rapid pace.  The MSU campus provides adequate backstopping and careful supervision for its generally high quality personnel in Nigeria. The physical plant at Nsukka has been developed and accomodates 2,000 students.  The University farm has been developed.  The Enugu campus has been made operational.  Administrative and academic organizations have been developed and staff recruited.  A continuing education program is operating.  And an Economic Development Institute has been initated at the Enugu Campus. The University graduated 143 students in 1963, 189 in 1964, and from 1965 onward it will graduate more than 500 per year, building to a maximum total enrollment of 6,000 students.  The output from the University will contribute significantly to Nigeria's estimated need of 2,000 graduates each year. The University is quickly moving to use more Nigerian staff.  58% of the 250 faculty members are now Nigerian.  It was hoped that the Vice Chancellorship would be assumed by a Nigerian in 1964, but this has not proved possible. The University has firmly established its non-traditional land grant philosophy based on the principle that the total program must grow out of the demonstrated needs of Nigeria. The stress at the University on African Studies, on Nigerianized content, on general studies, and on admitting only those students with the West African School Certificate has affected educational thought at both the university and high school level.  Broader curricular offerings have resulted.  The University, while still facing criticisms, is gaining prestige rapidly.

Abstract: EVALUATES, FROM 6/62 TO 2/29/64, REGIONAL TECHNICAL AIDS CENTER/PARIS (RTAC). RTAC PURPOSE IS TO TRANSLATE TECHNICAL/TRAINING MATERIALS FROM ENGLISH TO FRENCH/ARABIC FOR DISTRIBUTION TO USAID'S. EVALUATION IS BASED ON VISITS TO AID/W AND RTAC. RTAC WAS TRANSFERRED FROM RABAT, MOROCCO TO PARIS 1/63 TO OBTAIN BETTER TRANSLATORS AND PRINTING FACILITIES. OF FY 64 $180,000 ALLOTTED FUNDS, $107,828 ARE UNDISBURSED. $30,000 CAN PROBABLY BE DEOBLIGATED BY 6/64. SALARY COSTS APPEAR EXCESSIVE IN RELATION TO RTAC BUSINESS VOLUME. IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT AID/W CONSIDER REDUCING RTAC STAFF AND DISPATCHING A SHORT-TERM SPECIALIST TO ADVISE RTAC ON PROGRAM TECHNICAL ASPECTS. RTAC HAS TRANSLATED/PUBLISHED 4,600 PAGES INVOLVING 125,000 COPIES OF 76 PAMPHLETS AND IS WORKING ON 34 MORE BOOKS. 80,000 COPIES HAVE BEEN SENT TO USAID'S. TRANSLATIONS ARE INEXPENSIVE AND SUPERIOR TO THOSE OBTAINABLE ELSEWHERE. FOR THE SAKE OF EXPANSION, IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT RTAC COORDINATE ITS PROGRAM WITH THAT OF THE ORGANIZATION FOR ECONOMIC COOPERATION AND DEVELOPMENT (OECD). RTAC HAS SUBSIDIZED BOOKS FOR AN AMERICAN FIRM IN PARIS. BOOKS ARE LARGELY THEORETICAL, FOR WHICH THERE IS LITTLE MARKET IN AFRICAN COLONIES WHICH LACK, MOREOVER, PUBLICATIONS IN ELEMENTARY EDUCATION. IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT BOOK PUBLISHING BE DIRECTED TOWARD PRACTICAL MATERIALS (RTAC HAS COMPLIED WITH THIS) AND THAT RTAC DISCONTINUE SUBSIDY PUBLISHING IN EUROPE (TO SAVE COSTS) AND DEVELOP PUBLISHING/PRINTING IN AFRICA. RTAC HAS REQUESTED PERMISSION TO USE $30,000 OT ITS FY 64 ALLOTMENT FOR DUBBING SERVICES OF OECD AND OTHERS (REQUEST HAS BEEN GRANTED). PARIS EFFORTS OF THE UNITED STATES INFORMATION AGENCY (USIA) DO NOT DUPLICATE THOSE OF RTAC. STILL, RTAC AND USIA SHOULD NOT BE COMBINED, BUT RTAC SHOULD LOOK INTO USIA'S BOOK SUBSIDY POLICY FOR POSSIBLE ADOPTION WITH BOOKS OF POTENTIALLY WIDE SPREAD DISTRIBUTION. RTAC'S RECORDS/BOOKKEEPING ARE PRIMITIVE AND DISORGANIZED. IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT RTAC/PARIS ADOPT THE RECORD-KEEPING SYSTEM USED AT RTAC/MEXICO (FOR WHICH MATERIALS HAVE BEEN PROVIDED); TRAIN A SECRETARY TO KEEP SUCH RECORDS; AND ELIMINATE THE POSITION OF ACCOUNTANT.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1 Jun 1962-29 Feb 1964
